==============================================================
SINGLY LINKED LIST NOTES
==============================================================

1) What is a Singly Linked List?
--------------------------------------------------------------
- A singly linked list is a linear data structure.
- It is made of nodes.
- Each node contains:
  1. data
  2. next pointer/reference

- The next pointer stores the address of the next node.
- The last node points to null.

Diagram:
head
 |
 v
+---------+---------+      +---------+---------+      +---------+---------+
|    0    |  next   | ---> |    1    |  next   | ---> |    2    |  null   |
+---------+---------+      +---------+---------+      +---------+---------+

--------------------------------------------------------------

2) Structure of One Node
--------------------------------------------------------------
Each node has 2 parts:

+---------+---------+
|  data   |  next   |
+---------+---------+

Example:
+---------+---------+
|   10    |   *     |
+---------+---------+

- data = actual value
- next = address/reference of next node

--------------------------------------------------------------

3) Meaning of Head
--------------------------------------------------------------
- head is the starting pointer of the linked list.
- It stores the address of the first node.
- Using head, we can traverse the whole list.


4) Meaning of Tail
--------------------------------------------------------------
- tail is the last node of the linked list.
- Its next pointer is always null.


5) Why it is called "Singly"
--------------------------------------------------------------
- It is called singly linked list because
  each node points in only one direction:
  forward direction.


6) Main Properties
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Dynamic size
- Non-contiguous memory
- Sequential access
- Easy insertion/deletion at known position
- Extra memory needed for pointer


7) Traversal in Singly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
To print or visit all nodes:
- start from head
- move node by node using next
- stop when current becomes null


8) Important Point About Access
--------------------------------------------------------------
- In array, we can directly access arr[i]
- In linked list, direct indexing is not possible

To reach 3rd node:
- start from head
- move one by one

Example:
head
 |
 v
[10|*] -> [20|*] -> [30|*] -> [40|null]

To reach 30:
- first go to 10
- then 20
- then 30



13) Advantages of Singly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Dynamic size
- Easy insertion at beginning
- Easy deletion if previous node is known
- Better than array when many insertions/deletions happen

--------------------------------------------------------------

14) Disadvantages of Singly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- No random access
- Extra memory for next pointer
- Traversal is slower than array
- Cannot move backward directly
- Searching takes more time


15) Time Complexity
--------------------------------------------------------------
Operation                  Time
--------------------------------------------------------------
Access by position         O(n)
Search                     O(n)
Insert at beginning        O(1)
Insert at end              O(n)   // O(1) if tail is maintained
Delete at beginning        O(1)
Delete by value/position   O(n)

--------------------------------------------------------------

16) Real Interview One-Liner
--------------------------------------------------------------
A singly linked list is a linear data structure
where each node stores data and the reference
to the next node, allowing only forward traversal.

--------------------------------------------------------------

17) Very Short Revision Note
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Node = data + next
- head = first node
- tail = last node
- last node points to null
- forward traversal only
- no direct indexing
- insertion/deletion easier than array

